# Vinzor Document Generator — Complete Implementation Package

A template-driven Excel + VBA + Word platform that generates legal / financial transaction documents from Word templates. Adding a new transaction type requires **only** a new Word template plus **one** row on the Config sheet — never a code change.

Everything that touches Word or the Scripting runtime is **late bound** (`CreateObject`), so the workbook needs no VBA references. The original template is never opened for editing; every document is built from a private working copy.

---

## Fastest path to a working file

1. Create a new macro-enabled workbook (`.xlsm`).
2. Open the VBA editor (`Alt`+`F11`). Add one standard module for each `.bas` file below and one class module for `clsAltSection`, then paste each file's contents in. Paste the two worksheet snippets behind `ThisWorkbook` and the Dashboard sheet (Part 7).
3. Back in Excel, run the macro **`SetupWorkbook`** once (`Alt`+`F8` → `SetupWorkbook` → Run). It builds every sheet, named range, dropdown and button automatically.
4. Drop your `.docx` templates into a `Templates` subfolder next to the workbook (or edit the paths on the Config sheet).
5. Use the Dashboard: pick a type → **Load Transaction** → fill in values → **Generate Document**.

> If you would rather not hand-create the modules, import the accompanying `.bas` / `.cls` files directly (VBA editor → *File ▸ Import File…*), then still paste the two Part 7 snippets behind their objects and run `SetupWorkbook`.

---

## PART 1 — Workbook Design

### Goal and operating model

The workbook is a thin, generic shell. All knowledge that varies by transaction type lives **outside** the VBA: in the Word templates (which tags exist) and in the Config sheet (which template maps to which type and sheet). The code reads those at run time and adapts.

Two tag kinds are understood inside templates:

- **Placeholders** — `<<Name>>`, e.g. `<<Counterparty>>`, `<<PurchasePrice>>`, `<<Leg1_ISIN>>`. Replaced with values.
- **ALT blocks** — optional regions delimited by `<<ALT_Section_Option_START>>` … `<<ALT_Section_Option_END>>`. The user picks one option per section (or *None*); the chosen block is kept with its markers stripped, all sibling blocks are deleted.

### End-to-end flow

1. User opens the workbook → lands on the **Dashboard**.
2. User selects a **Transaction Type** (dropdown sourced from Config).
3. User clicks **Load Transaction**. The engine resolves the template path, opens it invisibly via late-bound Word, harvests text from every story (body, tables, headers, footers, text boxes, shapes), extracts and de-duplicates placeholders and ALT sections, writes them to two hidden working sheets, and builds the visible **transaction input sheet** (fields + ALT dropdowns).
4. User fills in master inputs (on the Dashboard) and transaction-specific inputs (on the transaction sheet), and chooses ALT options.
5. User clicks **Generate Document**. The engine copies the template to TEMP, processes ALT sections, replaces every placeholder everywhere, removes excessive blank paragraphs, scans for anything unresolved, saves the final `.docx` next to the workbook, and opens it in a visible Word window.

### Design principles

- **Template-driven / zero-maintenance placeholders.** The placeholder and ALT tables are rebuilt from the template on every load; nothing is hand-maintained.
- **No hardcoded paths.** Template locations live only on Config and support a `{WB}` token (the workbook's own folder) plus absolute and relative paths.
- **Late binding only.** Word and `Scripting.Dictionary` are created with `CreateObject`. No references to set, nothing to break across Office versions.
- **Never mutate the original.** Generation always runs on a throwaway copy in TEMP.
- **Master fields are shared, never duplicated.** Fields present in the master table are excluded from each transaction sheet.
- **Round-trip-safe ALT handling.** The real option key is stored verbatim, so START/END markers reconstruct exactly even for unusual names.

## PART 2 — Sheet Structure

| Sheet | Visibility | Purpose |
|-------|------------|---------|
| `Dashboard` | Visible | Main UI: type selector, Load/Generate buttons, status line, master input table. |
| `Config` | Visible (may be hidden) | Maps each transaction type to its template path, transaction sheet, and description. |
| `Transaction_*` | Visible on demand | One per type (e.g. `Transaction_GMRA`). Auto-created/rebuilt on load. Holds transaction-specific fields and ALT dropdowns. |
| `wPlaceholders` | Very hidden | Working sheet: the de-duplicated placeholder names from the last scan. |
| `wAlt` | Very hidden | Working sheet: ALT sections — `Section`, `OptionLabel`, real `FullKey` — from the last scan. |

### Dashboard layout

| Cell | Content |
|------|---------|
| `B2` | Title — “Vinzor — Document Generator” |
| `B4` | Label “Transaction Type:” |
| `C4` | **Transaction Type** dropdown (named `nTransType`) |
| `B6` | Label “Status:” |
| `C6` | Status message (named `nStatus`) |
| `E4` | **Load Transaction** button |
| `G4` | **Generate Document** button |
| `B9` | Section header “MASTER INPUTS” |
| `B11:C11` | Master table header (`Field` / `Value`) |
| `B12:C…` | Master fields and values (range `nMasterTable` covers `B12:C60`) |

Default master fields seeded by setup: `Counterparty`, `TradeDate`, `EffectiveDate`, `Currency`, `NoticeEmail`, `GoverningLaw`. Add or remove rows freely within `B12:C60`.

### Config layout

| Column | Header | Meaning |
|--------|--------|---------|
| `A` | Transaction Type | Must match the dropdown value exactly. |
| `B` | Template Path | `{WB}\Templates\X.docx`, absolute, or relative. |
| `C` | Transaction Sheet | Sheet name to build (e.g. `Transaction_GMRA`). |
| `D` | Description | Free text. |

Data rows start at row 2; range `nConfigTable` covers `A2:D200`. **To add a transaction type, add a row here and drop in its template — nothing else.**

### Transaction sheet layout (built automatically)

| Region | Cells | Content |
|--------|-------|---------|
| Title | `B1` | “*Type* — Transaction Inputs” |
| Field/value header | `B3:C3` | `Field` / `Value` |
| Field/value rows | `B4:C…` | One row per non-master placeholder; value cell shaded for entry. |
| ALT header | `E3:F3` | `Optional Section` / `Selection` |
| ALT rows | `E4:F…` | One dropdown per ALT section; options + `None`, defaulting to `None`. |

## PART 3 — Named Ranges

All four are created (and re-created safely) by `SetupWorkbook`.

| Name | Refers to | Used for |
|------|-----------|----------|
| `nTransType` | `Dashboard!$C$4` | The selected transaction type. |
| `nStatus` | `Dashboard!$C$6` | Status message cell. |
| `nMasterTable` | `Dashboard!$B$12:$C$60` | Master field/value table. |
| `nConfigTable` | `Config!$A$2:$D$200` | Config data rows. |

The ranges are intentionally generous (to row 60 / 200) and are scanned with blank-terminated loops, so unused rows cost nothing and you can grow the tables without redefining names.

## PART 4 — Buttons and Controls

### Buttons (Form controls, added by setup)

| Button | Cell anchor | Macro (`OnAction`) |
|--------|-------------|--------------------|
| Load Transaction | `E4` | `LoadTransaction` |
| Generate Document | `G4` | `GenerateDocument` |

Form-control buttons are used (not ActiveX) for portability and to avoid reference/registration issues. `SetupWorkbook` removes any existing buttons before adding fresh ones, so it is safe to re-run.

### Data validation (dropdowns)

- **Transaction Type** (`Dashboard!C4`): list validation sourced from `Config!$A$2:$A$200`.
- **ALT selections** (transaction sheet, column `F`): per-section list validation built from that section's options plus `None`. If a section's option list would exceed Excel's ~255-character inline limit, that cell falls back to free-text entry rather than failing.

### Manual button setup (only if not using `SetupWorkbook`)

Developer ▸ Insert ▸ Form Controls ▸ Button. Draw it, then in the *Assign Macro* dialog choose `LoadTransaction` (or `GenerateDocument`). Repeat for the second button.

## PART 5 — VBA Architecture

Eight code components, each with a single responsibility. Arrows show the call direction at the two entry points.

- **`modUtils`** (Standard module) — Late-binding factories and file/sheet/string helpers.
- **`clsAltSection`** (Class module) — Holds the real ALT option keys for one section.
- **`modConfig`** (Standard module) — All names/constants plus Config & master accessors.
- **`modScanner`** (Standard module) — Opens the template, harvests text, parses tags, writes working sheets.
- **`modUI`** (Standard module) — Builds the transaction input sheet and reads entries back.
- **`modWordGen`** (Standard module) — The late-bound Word generation engine.
- **`modMain`** (Standard module) — The two button macros.
- **`modSetup`** (Standard module) — One-click workbook bootstrap.

**Load Transaction** → `modMain.LoadTransaction` → `modScanner.ScanTemplateAndBuild` → (`CollectTemplateText`, `ParseTags`, `WritePlaceholderSheet`, `WriteAltSheet`) → `modUI.BuildTransactionSheet`.

**Generate Document** → `modMain.GenerateDocument` → (`GetMasterValues`, `ReadTransactionInputs`, `ReadAltSelections`) → `modWordGen.BuildWordDocument` → (`ProcessAltSections`, `ReplaceAllPlaceholders`, `CleanupBlankParagraphs`, `ScanUnresolved`).

### Why these boundaries

- **`modConfig` owns every literal** (sheet names, range names, column offsets). Change a layout once, here, and the whole project follows.
- **`modUI` shares its layout constants between build and read**, so the sheet it writes is exactly the sheet it later parses.
- **`clsAltSection` stores real keys**, guaranteeing marker reconstruction is exact.
- **`modWordGen` is pure late binding** with its own copy of the handful of `wd*` numeric constants it needs.

### ALT processing order (critical)

ALT sections are resolved **before** placeholder replacement. That ordering means placeholders inside a *kept* block still get replaced, while placeholders inside a *deleted* block vanish with the block and never show up in the unresolved scan.

### Error handling

Every externally-triggered path has a handler that restores `ScreenUpdating`, writes a status, and shows a specific message. The engine raises described errors (`vbObjectError`-based) for: template not found, Word not installed, missing Config path/sheet, and open/copy/save failures. ALT structure problems (a `START` with no `END`, or vice versa) are reported as a non-fatal warning so the user can still inspect the result.

## PART 6 — Complete VBA Code

Paste each block into a module of the matching type (or import the files). All modules use `Option Explicit`.

### `modUtils` — Standard module

*Late-binding factories and file/sheet/string helpers.*

```vba
Attribute VB_Name = "modUtils"
'=================================================================
' modUtils
' Low-level, dependency-free helpers shared across the project.
'
' All access to Word and the Scripting runtime is LATE BOUND here.
' No project references are required for any of this to compile.
'=================================================================
Option Explicit

' Custom error base. Anything we Raise uses vbObjectError + offset
' so the numbers never collide with native VBA/Office error codes.
Public Const ERR_BASE As Long = vbObjectError + 1500

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Late-bound Scripting.Dictionary factory.
' Used everywhere instead of a referenced Scripting.Dictionary so
' the workbook carries no library reference.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function NewDict() As Object
    Set NewDict = CreateObject("Scripting.Dictionary")
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Late-bound VBScript RegExp factory.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function NewRegExp() As Object
    Set NewRegExp = CreateObject("VBScript.RegExp")
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Late-bound Word.Application factory.
' Raises a clean, described error if Word is not installed so the
' caller can show a friendly message instead of an automation crash.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function NewWordApp() As Object
    On Error GoTo NoWord
    Set NewWordApp = CreateObject("Word.Application")
    Exit Function
NoWord:
    Err.Raise ERR_BASE + 1, "NewWordApp", _
        "Microsoft Word could not be started. Word must be installed " & _
        "on this machine to load templates and generate documents."
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Returns True if a worksheet with the given name exists in ThisWorkbook.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function SheetExists(ByVal sheetName As String) As Boolean
    Dim ws As Worksheet
    On Error Resume Next
    Set ws = ThisWorkbook.Worksheets(sheetName)
    On Error GoTo 0
    SheetExists = Not ws Is Nothing
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Ensures a worksheet with the given name exists and returns it.
' Creates it if missing. makeVisible controls whether the sheet is
' shown to the user or kept as a very-hidden working sheet.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function EnsureSheet(ByVal sheetName As String, _
                            ByVal makeVisible As Boolean) As Worksheet
    Dim ws As Worksheet
    If SheetExists(sheetName) Then
        Set ws = ThisWorkbook.Worksheets(sheetName)
    Else
        Set ws = ThisWorkbook.Worksheets.Add( _
            After:=ThisWorkbook.Worksheets(ThisWorkbook.Worksheets.Count))
        ws.Name = sheetName
    End If

    On Error Resume Next
    If makeVisible Then
        ws.Visible = xlSheetVisible
    Else
        ws.Visible = xlSheetVeryHidden
    End If
    On Error GoTo 0

    Set EnsureSheet = ws
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Path of the user's temp folder, no trailing separator.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function TempFolderPath() As String
    Dim p As String
    p = Environ$("TEMP")
    If Len(p) = 0 Then p = Environ$("TMP")
    If Len(p) = 0 Then p = ThisWorkbook.Path
    If Right$(p, 1) = "\" Then p = Left$(p, Len(p) - 1)
    TempFolderPath = p
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Deletes a file if it exists, swallowing any error (e.g. locked).
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub SafeKill(ByVal filePath As String)
    On Error Resume Next
    If Len(Dir$(filePath)) > 0 Then Kill filePath
    On Error GoTo 0
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' True if a file exists at the given path.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function FileExists(ByVal filePath As String) As Boolean
    On Error Resume Next
    FileExists = (Len(filePath) > 0) And (Len(Dir$(filePath)) > 0)
    On Error GoTo 0
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Joins a VBA.Collection of strings with the given separator.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function CollectionToText(ByVal col As Collection, _
                                 ByVal sep As String) As String
    Dim i As Long, s As String
    If col Is Nothing Then Exit Function
    For i = 1 To col.Count
        If i > 1 Then s = s & sep
        s = s & CStr(col.Item(i))
    Next i
    CollectionToText = s
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Last used row in a single column, scanning downward from startRow
' and stopping at the first blank cell (block-terminated, not the
' sheet's UsedRange). Returns startRow - 1 if the first cell is blank.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function LastRowIn(ByVal ws As Worksheet, _
                          ByVal col As Long, _
                          ByVal startRow As Long) As Long
    Dim r As Long
    r = startRow
    Do While Len(Trim$(CStr(ws.Cells(r, col).Value))) > 0
        r = r + 1
    Loop
    LastRowIn = r - 1
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' For an ALT key of the form "Section_Option", returns the Option
' part (everything AFTER the first underscore). If there is no
' underscore the whole key is returned.
' e.g. "Currency_USD"   -> "USD"
'      "Currency_USD_2" -> "USD_2"  (only the FIRST underscore splits)
'      "Flag"           -> "Flag"
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function OptionLabelFromKey(ByVal fullKey As String) As String
    Dim p As Long
    p = InStr(1, fullKey, "_")
    If p = 0 Then
        OptionLabelFromKey = fullKey
    Else
        OptionLabelFromKey = Mid$(fullKey, p + 1)
    End If
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' For an ALT key of the form "Section_Option", returns the Section
' part (everything BEFORE the first underscore). If there is no
' underscore the whole key is returned.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function SectionFromKey(ByVal fullKey As String) As String
    Dim p As Long
    p = InStr(1, fullKey, "_")
    If p = 0 Then
        SectionFromKey = fullKey
    Else
        SectionFromKey = Left$(fullKey, p - 1)
    End If
End Function
```

### `clsAltSection` — Class module

*Holds the real ALT option keys for one section.*

```vba
VERSION 1.0 CLASS
BEGIN
  MultiUse = -1  'True
END
Attribute VB_Name = "clsAltSection"
Attribute VB_GlobalNameSpace = False
Attribute VB_Creatable = False
Attribute VB_PredeclaredId = False
Attribute VB_Exposed = False
'=================================================================
' clsAltSection
' Represents one ALT Section discovered in a template (e.g. "Currency")
' and the set of Option keys found for it (e.g. "Currency_USD",
' "Currency_EUR").
'
' DESIGN NOTE (important):
' We store the REAL full key exactly as parsed from the template,
' never a recomputed "Section_Option" string. That guarantees the
' START/END markers can be reconstructed byte-for-byte when we strip
' or delete blocks later, even if a key contains extra underscores
' or only a single token.
'=================================================================
Option Explicit

Private pSectionName As String
Private pKeys As Collection      ' of String, the real full keys

Private Sub Class_Initialize()
    Set pKeys = New Collection
End Sub

Private Sub Class_Terminate()
    Set pKeys = Nothing
End Sub

'--- The section name (text before the first underscore of its keys).
Public Property Get SectionName() As String
    SectionName = pSectionName
End Property
Public Property Let SectionName(ByVal value As String)
    pSectionName = value
End Property

'--- Add a real full key. Deduplicated via a keyed collection trick.
Public Sub AddKey(ByVal fullKey As String)
    If HasKey(fullKey) Then Exit Sub
    pKeys.Add fullKey, "K::" & fullKey
End Sub

'--- True if this full key has already been recorded.
Public Function HasKey(ByVal fullKey As String) As Boolean
    Dim v As Variant
    On Error Resume Next
    v = pKeys.Item("K::" & fullKey)
    HasKey = (Err.Number = 0)
    On Error GoTo 0
End Function

'--- The collection of real full keys for this section.
Public Property Get Keys() As Collection
    Set Keys = pKeys
End Property

'--- Number of option keys recorded.
Public Property Get Count() As Long
    Count = pKeys.Count
End Property
```

### `modConfig` — Standard module

*All names/constants plus Config & master accessors.*

```vba
Attribute VB_Name = "modConfig"
'=================================================================
' modConfig
' Single home for every sheet name, named-range name, column offset
' and Config-sheet accessor in the project.
'
' No template path is ever hardcoded here. Paths live only in the
' Config worksheet and are resolved at run time.
'=================================================================
Option Explicit

'--- Worksheet names ------------------------------------------------
Public Const SHEET_DASHBOARD As String = "Dashboard"
Public Const SHEET_CONFIG    As String = "Config"
Public Const SHEET_PLACEHLDR As String = "wPlaceholders"  ' very hidden
Public Const SHEET_ALT       As String = "wAlt"           ' very hidden

'--- Named ranges ---------------------------------------------------
Public Const NR_TRANS_TYPE   As String = "nTransType"
Public Const NR_MASTER_TABLE As String = "nMasterTable"
Public Const NR_CONFIG_TABLE As String = "nConfigTable"
Public Const NR_STATUS       As String = "nStatus"

'--- Config table column offsets (relative to the config range) -----
Public Const CFG_COL_TYPE  As Long = 1   ' Transaction Type
Public Const CFG_COL_PATH  As Long = 2   ' Template Path
Public Const CFG_COL_SHEET As Long = 3   ' Associated Transaction Sheet
Public Const CFG_COL_DESC  As Long = 4   ' Template Description

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' The transaction type the user has currently selected on the
' Dashboard (named range nTransType). Trimmed. May be empty.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetSelectedTransactionType() As String
    On Error Resume Next
    GetSelectedTransactionType = _
        Trim$(CStr(ThisWorkbook.Names(NR_TRANS_TYPE).RefersToRange.Value))
    On Error GoTo 0
End Function

' Backwards-compatible alias used by some callers.
Public Function GetSelectedTransType() As String
    GetSelectedTransType = GetSelectedTransactionType()
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Writes a short status string to the Dashboard status cell.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub SetStatus(ByVal msg As String)
    On Error Resume Next
    ThisWorkbook.Names(NR_STATUS).RefersToRange.Value = msg
    On Error GoTo 0
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' The Config data range (named range nConfigTable). Row 1 of this
' range is the first DATA row (headers sit just above it).
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function ConfigData() As Range
    On Error Resume Next
    Set ConfigData = ThisWorkbook.Names(NR_CONFIG_TABLE).RefersToRange
    On Error GoTo 0
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Finds the Config row index (1-based, within the config range) for
' a given transaction type. Returns 0 if not found.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetConfigRowByType(ByVal transType As String) As Long
    Dim rng As Range, r As Long, cellVal As String
    Set rng = ConfigData()
    If rng Is Nothing Then Exit Function

    For r = 1 To rng.Rows.Count
        cellVal = Trim$(CStr(rng.Cells(r, CFG_COL_TYPE).Value))
        If Len(cellVal) = 0 Then Exit For          ' stop at first blank row
        If StrComp(cellVal, Trim$(transType), vbTextCompare) = 0 Then
            GetConfigRowByType = r
            Exit Function
        End If
    Next r
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Reads a single column value from the Config row of a given type.
' Returns "" if the type or value is not found.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetConfigValue(ByVal transType As String, _
                               ByVal colOffset As Long) As String
    Dim rng As Range, r As Long
    r = GetConfigRowByType(transType)
    If r = 0 Then Exit Function
    Set rng = ConfigData()
    GetConfigValue = Trim$(CStr(rng.Cells(r, colOffset).Value))
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Raw (unresolved) template path for a type, straight from Config.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetTemplatePathForType(ByVal transType As String) As String
    GetTemplatePathForType = GetConfigValue(transType, CFG_COL_PATH)
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Transaction sheet name associated with a type.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetTransactionSheetForType(ByVal transType As String) As String
    GetTransactionSheetForType = GetConfigValue(transType, CFG_COL_SHEET)
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Human-readable description for a type.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetTemplateDescriptionForType(ByVal transType As String) As String
    GetTemplateDescriptionForType = GetConfigValue(transType, CFG_COL_DESC)
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Resolves a raw Config path into an absolute path.
'  - Absolute paths (drive "X:\..." or UNC "\\server\...") are used as-is.
'  - The token {WB} expands to ThisWorkbook.Path.
'  - Anything else is treated as relative to ThisWorkbook.Path.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function ResolveTemplatePath(ByVal rawPath As String) As String
    Dim p As String
    p = Trim$(rawPath)
    If Len(p) = 0 Then Exit Function

    ' Expand the workbook-folder token first.
    If InStr(1, p, "{WB}", vbTextCompare) > 0 Then
        p = Replace(p, "{WB}", ThisWorkbook.Path, 1, -1, vbTextCompare)
    End If

    ' Already absolute? (drive-letter colon or UNC double-backslash)
    If Mid$(p, 2, 1) = ":" Or Left$(p, 2) = "\\" Then
        ResolveTemplatePath = p
        Exit Function
    End If

    ' Otherwise relative to the workbook folder.
    If Left$(p, 1) = "\" Then p = Mid$(p, 2)
    ResolveTemplatePath = ThisWorkbook.Path & "\" & p
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Convenience: resolved, absolute template path for a type.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetResolvedTemplatePath(ByVal transType As String) As String
    GetResolvedTemplatePath = ResolveTemplatePath(GetTemplatePathForType(transType))
End Function

'=================================================================
' Master input accessors
' The master table (named range nMasterTable) is a two-column table:
'   col 1 = field name, col 2 = value.
' Master fields are shared across every transaction type.
'=================================================================

'--- The master table range (nMasterTable).
Public Function GetMasterTable() As Range
    On Error Resume Next
    Set GetMasterTable = ThisWorkbook.Names(NR_MASTER_TABLE).RefersToRange
    On Error GoTo 0
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' A case-insensitive set of master field names (Dictionary whose
' keys are the field names). Used to exclude master fields from the
' per-transaction input table so nothing is duplicated.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetMasterFieldNames() As Object
    Dim d As Object, rng As Range, r As Long, nm As String
    Set d = NewDict()
    d.CompareMode = 1                       ' vbTextCompare -> case-insensitive
    Set rng = GetMasterTable()
    If rng Is Nothing Then
        Set GetMasterFieldNames = d
        Exit Function
    End If
    For r = 1 To rng.Rows.Count
        nm = Trim$(CStr(rng.Cells(r, 1).Value))
        If Len(nm) = 0 Then Exit For
        If Not d.Exists(nm) Then d.Add nm, True
    Next r
    Set GetMasterFieldNames = d
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' A Dictionary of master field name -> value.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function GetMasterValues() As Object
    Dim d As Object, rng As Range, r As Long, nm As String
    Set d = NewDict()
    d.CompareMode = 1
    Set rng = GetMasterTable()
    If rng Is Nothing Then
        Set GetMasterValues = d
        Exit Function
    End If
    For r = 1 To rng.Rows.Count
        nm = Trim$(CStr(rng.Cells(r, 1).Value))
        If Len(nm) = 0 Then Exit For
        If Not d.Exists(nm) Then d.Add nm, CStr(rng.Cells(r, 2).Value)
    Next r
    Set GetMasterValues = d
End Function
```

### `modScanner` — Standard module

*Opens the template, harvests text, parses tags, writes working sheets.*

```vba
Attribute VB_Name = "modScanner"
'=================================================================
' modScanner
' Loads a template via late-bound Word, harvests its text from every
' story (body, tables, headers/footers, textboxes, shapes), parses
' out placeholders and ALT sections, writes them to the two working
' sheets, and triggers the transaction-sheet build.
'
' Word handling rule: we ALWAYS create a fresh, invisible Word
' instance and Quit it when done. We never attach to an instance the
' user already has open (GetObject), so we can never hide or close
' the user's own Word session.
'=================================================================
Option Explicit

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Public entry point. Scans the template for a transaction type and
' rebuilds its working sheets + transaction sheet.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub ScanTemplateAndBuild(ByVal transType As String)
    Dim tplPath As String
    Dim sheetName As String
    Dim wdApp As Object
    Dim wdDoc As Object
    Dim fullText As String
    Dim placeholders As Object       ' Dictionary: name -> True
    Dim sections As Object           ' Dictionary: section -> clsAltSection

    '--- Validate configuration before opening anything.
    tplPath = GetResolvedTemplatePath(transType)
    If Len(tplPath) = 0 Then
        Err.Raise ERR_BASE + 101, "ScanTemplateAndBuild", _
            "No template path is configured for transaction type '" & _
            transType & "'. Add it on the Config sheet."
    End If
    If Not FileExists(tplPath) Then
        Err.Raise ERR_BASE + 102, "ScanTemplateAndBuild", _
            "Template file was not found:" & vbCrLf & tplPath
    End If

    sheetName = GetTransactionSheetForType(transType)
    If Len(sheetName) = 0 Then
        Err.Raise ERR_BASE + 103, "ScanTemplateAndBuild", _
            "No transaction sheet name is configured for '" & _
            transType & "'. Add it on the Config sheet."
    End If

    '--- Open the template (read only, invisible) and harvest text.
    On Error GoTo CleanFail
    Set wdApp = NewWordApp()
    wdApp.Visible = False
    On Error Resume Next
    wdApp.DisplayAlerts = 0          ' wdAlertsNone
    On Error GoTo CleanFail

    Set wdDoc = wdApp.Documents.Open(FileName:=tplPath, _
                                     ReadOnly:=True, _
                                     AddToRecentFiles:=False, _
                                     Visible:=False)

    fullText = CollectTemplateText(wdDoc)

    wdDoc.Close SaveChanges:=False   ' wdDoNotSaveChanges
    Set wdDoc = Nothing
    wdApp.Quit
    Set wdApp = Nothing

    '--- Parse and persist.
    Set placeholders = NewDict()
    Set sections = NewDict()
    ParseTags fullText, placeholders, sections

    WritePlaceholderSheet placeholders
    WriteAltSheet sections

    '--- Build the visible input sheet.
    BuildTransactionSheet transType

    Exit Sub

CleanFail:
    Dim em As String
    em = Err.Description
    On Error Resume Next
    If Not wdDoc Is Nothing Then wdDoc.Close SaveChanges:=False
    If Not wdApp Is Nothing Then wdApp.Quit
    Set wdDoc = Nothing
    Set wdApp = Nothing
    On Error GoTo 0
    Err.Raise ERR_BASE + 104, "ScanTemplateAndBuild", em
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Concatenates text from every story range in the document so the
' tag parser sees a single string covering body, tables, headers,
' footers, textboxes and shapes.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Function CollectTemplateText(ByVal wdDoc As Object) As String
    Dim sb As String
    Dim st As Object
    Dim shp As Object
    Dim sec As Object
    Dim i As Long

    '--- All story ranges (body + linked text box / footnote stories).
    On Error Resume Next
    Set st = wdDoc.StoryRanges.Item(1)   ' wdMainTextStory baseline
    On Error GoTo 0

    Dim story As Object
    For Each story In wdDoc.StoryRanges
        Set st = story
        Do While Not st Is Nothing
            sb = sb & st.Text & vbCrLf
            Set st = st.NextStoryRange
        Loop
    Next story

    '--- Shapes anchored in the body (text boxes etc.).
    On Error Resume Next
    For Each shp In wdDoc.Shapes
        If shp.TextFrame.HasText Then
            sb = sb & shp.TextFrame.TextRange.Text & vbCrLf
        End If
    Next shp
    On Error GoTo 0

    '--- Per-section headers and footers (primary / first / even) and
    '    any shapes living inside them.
    For Each sec In wdDoc.Sections
        sb = sb & HeaderFooterText(sec)
    Next sec

    CollectTemplateText = sb
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Returns concatenated text of all header and footer variants for a
' section, including shapes inside those headers/footers.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Private Function HeaderFooterText(ByVal sec As Object) As String
    Dim sb As String
    Dim idx As Long
    Dim hf As Object
    Dim shp As Object

    On Error Resume Next
    ' Indices 1..3 == primary, first page, even page.
    For idx = 1 To 3
        Set hf = sec.Headers.Item(idx)
        If Not hf Is Nothing Then
            If hf.Exists Then
                sb = sb & hf.Range.Text & vbCrLf
                For Each shp In hf.Shapes
                    If shp.TextFrame.HasText Then
                        sb = sb & shp.TextFrame.TextRange.Text & vbCrLf
                    End If
                Next shp
            End If
        End If

        Set hf = sec.Footers.Item(idx)
        If Not hf Is Nothing Then
            If hf.Exists Then
                sb = sb & hf.Range.Text & vbCrLf
                For Each shp In hf.Shapes
                    If shp.TextFrame.HasText Then
                        sb = sb & shp.TextFrame.TextRange.Text & vbCrLf
                    End If
                Next shp
            End If
        End If
    Next idx
    On Error GoTo 0

    HeaderFooterText = sb
End Function

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Parses all <<...>> tags out of text.
'   - Tags beginning ALT_ are classified into ALT sections.
'   - Everything else is a placeholder.
' placeholders : Dictionary populated with name -> True (deduped).
' sections     : Dictionary populated with section -> clsAltSection.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub ParseTags(ByVal text As String, _
                     ByRef placeholders As Object, _
                     ByRef sections As Object)
    Dim re As Object, matches As Object, m As Object
    Dim inner As String

    Dim startKeys As Object, endKeys As Object
    Set startKeys = NewDict()
    Set endKeys = NewDict()

    Set re = NewRegExp()
    re.Global = True
    re.IgnoreCase = False
    re.MultiLine = True
    re.Pattern = "<<([^<>]+?)>>"

    Set matches = re.Execute(text)
    For Each m In matches
        inner = Trim$(m.SubMatches(0))
        If Len(inner) = 0 Then GoTo NextMatch

        If Left$(inner, 4) = "ALT_" Then
            ClassifyAltTag inner, sections, startKeys, endKeys
        Else
            If Not placeholders.Exists(inner) Then placeholders.Add inner, True
        End If
NextMatch:
    Next m

    ValidateAltPairing startKeys, endKeys
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Classifies a single ALT tag inner-string (already stripped of <<>>).
' Expected forms:
'   ALT_<Section>_<Option>_START
'   ALT_<Section>_<Option>_END
' The Section is the text before the first underscore of the remainder
' after "ALT_"; the Option is everything between that and the _START/
' _END suffix. The real full key (Section_Option) is recorded on the
' section object exactly as derived.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Private Sub ClassifyAltTag(ByVal inner As String, _
                           ByRef sections As Object, _
                           ByRef startKeys As Object, _
                           ByRef endKeys As Object)
    Dim body As String
    Dim isStart As Boolean, isEnd As Boolean
    Dim fullKey As String
    Dim sectionName As String
    Dim sec As clsAltSection

    body = Mid$(inner, 5)            ' drop leading "ALT_"

    If Right$(body, 6) = "_START" Then
        isStart = True
        fullKey = Left$(body, Len(body) - 6)
    ElseIf Right$(body, 4) = "_END" Then
        isEnd = True
        fullKey = Left$(body, Len(body) - 4)
    Else
        ' Not a well-formed START/END marker: ignore quietly.
        Exit Sub
    End If

    If Len(fullKey) = 0 Then Exit Sub

    sectionName = SectionFromKey(fullKey)

    If sections.Exists(sectionName) Then
        Set sec = sections.Item(sectionName)
    Else
        Set sec = New clsAltSection
        sec.SectionName = sectionName
        sections.Add sectionName, sec
    End If
    sec.AddKey fullKey

    If isStart Then
        If Not startKeys.Exists(fullKey) Then startKeys.Add fullKey, True
    ElseIf isEnd Then
        If Not endKeys.Exists(fullKey) Then endKeys.Add fullKey, True
    End If
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Non-fatal validation that every START has an END and vice versa.
' Broken structures are surfaced to the user but do not abort the
' load, so they can still inspect and fix the template.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Private Sub ValidateAltPairing(ByVal startKeys As Object, _
                               ByVal endKeys As Object)
    Dim k As Variant, missing As String

    For Each k In startKeys.Keys
        If Not endKeys.Exists(k) Then
            missing = missing & " - <<ALT_" & k & "_START>> has no matching _END" & vbCrLf
        End If
    Next k
    For Each k In endKeys.Keys
        If Not startKeys.Exists(k) Then
            missing = missing & " - <<ALT_" & k & "_END>> has no matching _START" & vbCrLf
        End If
    Next k

    If Len(missing) > 0 Then
        MsgBox "Warning: the template has unbalanced ALT markers." & vbCrLf & vbCrLf & _
               missing & vbCrLf & _
               "These sections may not behave correctly. You can still " & _
               "continue, but consider fixing the template.", _
               vbExclamation, "ALT structure check"
    End If
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Writes the deduped placeholder names into the very-hidden
' wPlaceholders sheet (one name per row in column A from row 2).
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub WritePlaceholderSheet(ByVal placeholders As Object)
    Dim ws As Worksheet, r As Long, k As Variant
    Set ws = EnsureSheet(SHEET_PLACEHLDR, False)
    ws.Cells.Clear
    ws.Range("A1").Value = "PlaceholderName"

    r = 2
    For Each k In placeholders.Keys
        ws.Cells(r, 1).Value = CStr(k)
        r = r + 1
    Next k
End Sub

'-----------------------------------------------------------------
' Writes ALT sections into the very-hidden wAlt sheet:
'   A = Section, B = Option label, C = real full key.
' One row per option key. Used to build dropdowns and to drive block
' keep/delete during generation.
'-----------------------------------------------------------------
Public Sub WriteAltSheet(ByVal sections As Object)
    Dim ws As Worksheet, r As Long
    Dim secKey As Variant, keyVar As Variant
    Dim sec As clsAltSection
    Dim fullKey As String

    Set ws = EnsureSheet(SHEET_ALT, False)
    ws.Cells.Clear
    ws.Range("A1").Value = "Section"
    ws.Range("B1").Value = "OptionLabel"
    ws.Range("C1").Value = "FullKey"

    r = 2
    For Each secKey In sections.Keys
        Set sec = sections.Item(secKey)
        For Each keyVar In sec.Keys
            fullKey = CStr(keyVar)
            ws.Cells(r, 1).Value = sec.SectionName
            ws.Cells(r, 2).Value = OptionLabelFromKey(fullKey)
            ws.Cells(r, 3).Value = fullKey
            r = r + 1
        Next keyVar
    Next secKey
End Sub
